Leaflet Vignette

Katy Miles

Leaflet is originally a javascript library for creating customizable, interactive maps. The R Leaflet package allows the ability to have access to the javascript library with the convenience of R.

Reasons To Use Leaflet

Ive found that Leaflet is a great tool for performing EDA on spatial data, especially if you want an interactive map. The code set-up is pretty minimal compared to the amount of features you can get. It is also a nice option for creating maps for presentation or explanation to a collaborator.

Getting Started

To get started using leaflet, you need to start with a base map. There are a variety of pre-set base maps to access. In this example I also set the display view for the base map using setView()

Creating a Base Map

library(leaflet)

# Load in data
data = read.csv("https://opendata.fcgov.com/resource/g87z-rviz.csv")


# Create a base map using a provider
basemap = leaflet(data) %>%
  addProviderTiles(provider = providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>%
  setView(lat = 40.585, lng = -105.0844, zoom = 12)
  
basemap

Adding Data to A Base Map

Leaflet uses pipes to add layers to a base map. Below is a simple example of a base map with a data layer added on as points. Below is a list of the arguments I used and there purpose:

  • lat: Set the latitude for the points.

  • lng: Set the longitude for the points.

  • radius: Set the radius for the points, can be hard-coded or dependent on data.

  • label: Set what text appears in the pop-box when a point is hovered-over. Can be hard-coded or dependent on data.

Note that to reference a column from the data, a ~ is placed before the column name.

# Adding points to basemap with a radius dependent on a data variable
map = basemap %>%
        addCircles(lat = ~latitude, 
                    lng = ~longitude,
                     radius = 50, #In meters
                     fillOpacity = .3, 
                     label = ~sensor_name,
                     color = "#1A4458",
                     group = "Rainfall Sensors") 
map

Ading More Layers

There is a lot of room for customization in Leaflet. Here I show adding an additional data layer to the map as well as a legend. The addLayersControl() function was used to be able to hide or display data layers with a click box. The Leaflet function colorFactor() was used to make a color scale for my polygons.

library(geojsonio)

# Read in floodplain data
floodplain = geojsonio::geojson_read( "City Floodplain.geojson", what = "sp")

# Create color scale for floodplain risk
pal = colorFactor(c("#C25B41", "#ECA23D", "#F1C40F"), floodplain$risk)

map %>%
  addPolygons(data = floodplain, 
              color = ~pal(risk), 
              weight = 2, 
              fillOpacity = 1, 
              label = ~flood_type,
              group = "Floodplains") %>%
  addLegend(data = floodplain, 
            pal = pal, 
            values = ~risk,
            title = "Floodplain Risk",
            opacity = 1) %>%
  addLayersControl(overlayGroups = c("Rainfall Sensors", "Floodplains"),
                    options = layersControlOptions(collapsed = FALSE))
